__NOTOC__ {{Infobox named horse | horsename =Miss Jim 45 | image = | caption = - - | breed = [[American Quarter Horse|Quarter Horse]] | discipline = [[Halter (horse show)|Halter]] | sire = Jim Harlan | grandsire = Harlan | dam =Miss Paulo 45 | damsire = Paulos Dandy | sex = [[Mare]] | foaled =1966 | country = United States | color = [[Equine coat color#Less common coat colors|red dun]] | breeder = James Nance | owner = George Tyler, Frank Merrill | otherawards=1970 [[American Quarter Horse Association|AQHA]] High Point Halter Horse | honors = [[American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame]] |updated=January 12, 2008 }}
'''Miss Jim 45''' was a [[Equine coat color#Less common coat colors|red dun]] [[Quarter horse|Quarter Horse]] [[mare]] who won the 1970 [[American Quarter Horse Association]], or AQHA, High Point [[Halter (horse show)|Halter Horse]] Award.<ref name=Beckman>Beckman "Miss Jim 45" ''Quarter Horse Journal'' November 1991 p. 36, 121, & 123</ref>
She was a 1966 [[foal]], and her sire was Jim Harlan and her dam was a [[Waggoner Ranch]] mare named Miss Paulo 45.<ref name=Beckman/> Her sire traced back to [[King (horse)|King P-234]] as well as [[Peter McCue (horse)|Peter McCue]], [[Traveler (horse)|Traveler]] and [[Oklahoma Star (horse)|Oklahoma Star P-6]]. Her dam traced to many of the same sires, including King P-234, Traveler, Peter McCue and Yellow Jacket.<ref name=Pedigree>[http://www.allbreedpedigree.com/miss+jim+45 Miss Jim 45 pedigree at All Breed Pedigree] accessed on September 13, 2007</ref>
She earned 436 AQHA open [[Halter (horse show)|halter]] points that year, in 153 shows, placing first 139 times, second 12 times and one third and one fifth place. She was Grand Champion Mare all but 16 of those shows. Frank Merrill, who showed her to the title that year, said when he bought her, he was told by Matlock Rose that "Son, anyone could lead this horse into the ring and do just as well as me."<ref name=Beckman/> Besides her High Point award she also earned a Superior Halter Horse award with the AQHA.<ref name=QHR>Wagoner ''Quarter Horse Reference 1974 Edition'' p. 439</ref>
She died in 1978 and in 2000<ref name=MJ>{{cite web |title=Miss Jim 45 |url=https://www.aqha.com/museum/hall-of-fame/horses/m/miss-jim-45/ |work= AQHA Hall of Fame |author=American Quarter Horse Association (AQHA) |publisher=American Quarter Horse Association |accessdate=September 1, 2017 }}</ref> she was inducted into the AQHA [[American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame]].<ref name=MJ />
